"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434128","Home Office","false","2015-12-21","<p>All Tier 4 licensed sponsors are assessed against criteria set out in the published Tier 4 Guidance for Sponsors. This includes the following four documents:</p><ul><li>Document one – Applying for a Tier 4 licence</li><li>Document two – Sponsorship Duties</li><li>Document three – Tier 4 Compliance</li><li>Appendix D - record keeping</li></ul><p>Some of the key criteria includes:</p><ul><li>Ensuring that each sponsor has a genuine and lawful trading presence.</li><li>Ensuring that each sponsor holds the appropriate education oversight with the relevant external inspection body.</li><li>Compliance visits; where checks are undertaken to establish whether an institution’s HR functions are appropriate.</li><li>An annual basic compliance assessment (BCA); where the sponsor must meet demonstrate that their visa refusal, enrolment and course completion rates fall within the outlined requisites<em>.</em></li></ul>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-12-21T16:55:19.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434128/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434128/answer","Tier 4 Guidance 11-2015 - Documents 1-3 combined.pdf ; Appendix D.pdf","Tier 4 Guidance 11-2015 - Documents 1-3 combined.pdf ; Appendix D.pdf","Tier 4 Guidance - 1-3 Combined  ; Appendix D ","Tier 4 Guidance - 1-3 Combined  ; Appendix D ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434128/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-03","Visas: Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what criteria they use in auditing compliance with Tier 4 licences for non-EU students.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL4247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434129","Home Office","false","2015-12-16","<p>The number of Tier 4 licensed sponsors audited from 1 January to 30 September 2015 was 286. In the calendar year 2014 there were 383 .</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-12-16T17:15:36.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434129/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434129/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-03","Visas: Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many Tier 4 licences for non-EU students are audited annually.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL4248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434130","Home Office","false","2015-12-10","<p>The Tier 4 Register of Sponsors which is available via the link: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/register-of-licensed-sponsors-students shows active sponsors.</p><p>No information is routinely published regarding sponsors found not to be compliant.</p><p>In January 2015 data was published showing Tier 4 sponsors whose status appeared as revoked from 2010 to 2014. This information is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/tier-4-sponsors-whose-status-appeared-as-revoked-from-2010-to-2014</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-12-10T16:12:29.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434130/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434130/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-03","Visas: Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government where information about higher education institutions found not to be in compliance with Tier 4 licences for non-EU students is published.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL4249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434131","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-17","<p>The specific information requested is not held.</p><br /><p>Sentencing guidelines are issued by the independent Sentencing Council. They are available on the Sentencing Council website.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-12-17T15:46:48.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434131/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434131/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-03","Prison Sentences: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many women responsible for one or more young children are currently serving prison sentences in England and Wales, and what assessment they have made of the sentencing guidelines relating to such women.","false","Biography information for Lord Trefgarne",,"Lord Trefgarne","HL4250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434132","Department for Education","false","2015-12-15","<p>Schools in the maintained sector do not require an external audit as this is undertaken at local authority level.</p><p>Each academy trust’s audit fees vary reflecting a number of different factors such as the auditing firm used and the complexity of the business. We are, therefore, unable to provide an estimation of audit fees on a cost per pupil basis for a 1,000-pupil secondary school.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-12-15T13:34:31.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434132/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434132/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-03","Secondary Education: Audit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the estimated cost per pupil of auditing the accounts of a 1,000-pupil secondary school, in (1) the maintained sector, and (2) the academy sector.","false","Biography information for Lord Watson of Invergowrie",,"Lord Watson of Invergowrie","HL4251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434133","Department for Education","false","2015-12-15","<p>Academy trusts are charities, and must comply with charity law. As Principal Regulator the Secretary of State has a duty to promote this compliance by the charity trustees with their legal obligations in a trust’s management and administration.</p><p>The Charity Commission has powers of investigation and enforcement over academy trusts where the Secretary of State, as Principal Regulator, requests that the Commission investigates a concern that the Department has identified. This means that, in consultation with the Principal Regulator, the Charity Commission, will investigate and if a serious failure to comply with charity law is found, has the necessary enforcement powers to act if sanctions are required.</p><p>Academy trusts are exempt from registration and direct regulation by the Charity Commission and are instead overseen by a Principal Regulator. As PR, the Secretary of State has powers to investigate but enforcement powers rest with the Charity Commission.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-12-15T16:37:30.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434133/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434133/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-03","Academies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the remarks by Lord Nash on 1 December (HL Deb, col 1054), what is the role of the Charity Commission in scrutinising academies.","false","Biography information for Lord Watson of Invergowrie",,"Lord Watson of Invergowrie","HL4252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434134","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Department for Transport has a statutory obligation to deliver the Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy (CWIS) which is anticipated to include a National Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plan. The Department has commenced the early stages of work to develop the first CWIS by summer 2016 following a formal consultation in spring 2016. Detailed content of this Strategy is not yet available, and we are therefore unable to confirm our future plans for promoting walking to school initiatives at this stage.</p><br /><p>That said, the Government recently reaffirmed its commitment to cycling and walking by investing over £300m over the life of this Parliament. This includes delivering the Cycle City Ambition programme in full, and funding the Bikeability cycle training programme for school children. It also includes a new ‘Access’ fund for sustainable travel building on the legacy of the Local Sustainable Transport Fund. It is too early to say what the details of this new Access fund will be as discussions are ongoing, but information is expected to be available in the coming weeks.</p><br /><p>It is also worth noting that this Government remains committed to the principles of localism; it is therefore the responsibility of local authorities to decide their local priorities in relation to ‘walk to school’ initiatives, and attribute government resources, such as the local transport block, accordingly.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-12-17T16:03:55.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434134/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434134/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-03","Pupils: Walking","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what funding they plan to make available to promote walking to school initiatives when the Local Sustainable Transport Fund comes to an end in March 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Watson of Invergowrie",,"Lord Watson of Invergowrie","HL4253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434135","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-17","<p>Legislation that can be used to prosecute cyber-bullying related offences includes the Protection from Harassment Act 1997; the Public Order Act 1986; the Malicious Communications Act 1988; and the Communications Act 2003. The Criminal Justice and Courts Act 2015 made changes to the relevant offences in these last two Acts which will help to ensure that people who commit them are prosecuted and properly punished.</p><br /><p>The Government believes that this is sufficient and therefore does not intend to introduced specific additional legislation to address the issue of cyberbullying.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-12-17T14:06:15.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434135/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434135/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-03","Internet: Bullying","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proposals they have to strengthen legislation in order to prevent cyber bullying.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434136","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-21","<br /><p>An independent Review has been established to consider consumer protection measures in relation to online ticket resales and will report by 26 May 2016.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-12-21T12:21:33.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434136/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434136/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-03","Tickets: Touting","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the activities of ticket resale websites.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434137","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-16","<p>The Government has not undertaken an assessment of the co-operation between highway authorities and statutory undertakers.</p><br /><p>However, section 59 of the <em>New Roads and Street Works Act 1991</em> places a duty on local highway authorities to co-ordinate works on the highway and section 60 provides a mirror duty on statutory undertakers to co-operate with them in that role.</p><br /><p>Additionally the <em>Traffic Management Act 2004</em> introduced the Network Management Duty which requires local authorities to manage their networks with a view to making the most effective use of them. The 2004 Act also introduced permit schemes, which enable highway authorities to have a more proactive role in the management of their road networks.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-12-16T14:15:41.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434137/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434137/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-03","Road Works","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the co-operation between highway authorities and statutory service providers who need to dig up the highway and footway to maintain, repair and replace their services.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434138","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-17","<p>Setting local speed limits is a matter for the local highway authority, as they are best placed to determine the speed limits for their areas, based on local knowledge and the views of the community. The Department for Transport (DfT) has issued guidance to help them in Speed Limit Circular 01/2013 – Setting Local Speed Limits.</p><br /><p>In June 2014 the DfT commissioned a comprehensive three-year research project into the effects of 20mph limits. This will cover many aspects including effects on speed, collisions, casualties and modal shift. The research will also consider best practice, road users’ perceptions and effects on the quality of the environment.</p><br /> <br /> <br /> <br />",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-12-17T11:56:48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434138/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434138/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-03","Speed Limits","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the case for setting the speed limit at 20 miles per hour on all minor roads in villages, towns and cities.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434139","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-16","<p>Decisions about street lighting are primarily for elected local councillors, reflecting local circumstances and views. The Government has not made an assessment of the effects of turning off street lights in the early hours of the morning by some local authorities.</p><p>However, a research study - <em>The effect of reduced street lighting on road casualties and crime in England and Wales : controlled interrupted time series analysis</em> - by R Steinbach et al, in the Journal of Epidemiology and Community Health published in July 2015 on the effects of street lighting on road safety and crime in England and Wales (attached) found little evidence of harmful effects of switch off, part-night lighting, dimming, or changes to white light/LEDs on road collisions or crime.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-16T16:27:31.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434139/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434139/answer","HL4258 - The effect of reduced street lighting.pdf","HL4258 - The effect of reduced street lighting.pdf","The effect of reduced street lighting","The effect of reduced street lighting","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/434139/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-03","Roads: Lighting","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effects of turning off street lights in the early hours of the morning by some local authorities.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4258"
