"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433723","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-07","<br /> <br /><p>The Chair and Board Members will be appointed through public appointments. The outcome will be announced as soon as the process allows in 2016.</p><br /> <br /> <br />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-12-07T14:40:04.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433723/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433723/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-02","Institute for Apprenticeships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 1 December 2015 to Question 18024, when he plans for the membership of the Institute for Apprenticeships to be announced.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","18486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433724","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-07","<p>We are grateful for the insights and recommendations provided in Dame Ann Dowling’s Review of Business-University Research Collaborations. We recognise and support the conclusion it has reached and Innovate UK is already working to simplify its product offering. Alongside the recent Higher Education Green Paper and Sir Paul Nurse’sreport, it will now be taken forward in our review of the funding landscape to make it, as recommended by Dame Ann, more strategic, coherent and effective.</p><br />","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-07T15:13:39.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433724/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433724/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-02","Business-University Research Collaborations Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when the Government's response will be published to the Dowling Review of Business-University Research Collaborations.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","18473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433725","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 7 December 2015 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-12-02/18533/" target="_blank">18533</a>.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","18518","2015-12-07T16:10:35.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433725/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433725/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-02","Offshoring","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the (a) effect to date and (b) potential future effect on the UK skills base of the outsourcing of UK manufacturing and energy supply chain contracts to other EU member states.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","18515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433726","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 7 December 2015 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-12-02/18533/" target="_blank">18533</a>.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","18515","2015-12-07T16:10:36.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433726/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433726/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-02","Wind Power: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential economic effect on Scotland of Buchan Deep supply chain work being awarded to a company that will undertake the work overseas.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","18518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433727","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-09","<p>All employers with a pay bill greater than £3,000,000 will be in scope of the apprenticeships levy, including those in the construction and engineering construction sectors. We are working with the Industry Training Boards to understand how their existing arrangements will be affected. They will be consulting with their members in advance of the introduction of the apprenticeships levy on whether they should continue to pay the industry levy and if so, how it should be combined with the national apprenticeship levy. We are also working with other sectors, where there are existing collective training arrangements about what the apprenticeships levy means to them.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-12-09T10:04:08.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433727/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433727/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-02","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the potential overlap between contributors to the construction industry training levy and the proposed employer apprenticeship levy; and what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the construction industry of that proposed levy in drawing up those proposals.","false","Biography information for Nigel Adams","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","18522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433728","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-11","<p>As has been the case under successive Administrations, civil servants, including special advisers, may routinely accompany their Ministers on official visits</p><p><br> Information relating to Ministers' overseas visits is published on my Department’s website, as part of the Government’s wider transparency agenda.</p><p>All ministerial travel is undertaken in accordance with the Ministerial Code.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-11T12:49:09.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433728/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433728/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-02","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, on how many occasions a special adviser in his Department accompanied a Minister on an overseas trip since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","18493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433729","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-10","<p>The Government recognises that new businesses can encounter difficulties in obtaining the finance they need to start-up or grow. However I am encouraged that net lending to smaller businesses has been recovering strongly since the end of 2014. The Bank of England has reported that credit conditions for SMEs seeking finance are improving and the SME Finance Monitor shows that 80% of SME loan and overdraft applications were successful in the 18 months to 2015 Q3, up from 68% in Q4 2013.</p><p>Latest figures show that net SME lending from banks participating in the Funding for Lending Scheme grew by £675m in the third quarter and the Bank of England recently announced that allowances earned by banks for increasing their net lending under the scheme will be available to draw down for a further two years. The government also continues to fund start-up loans, with more than 33,000 loans worth over £180 million issued so far and a target to deliver 75,000 loans by the end of the parliament.</p><p>I am also encouraged by our growing alternative finance sector, with the UK the leading fin tech centre of Europe.</p><p>A recent report from the Legatum Institute rated the UK as the best country in the EU in which to start a business and the government will continue to back our small businesses to start and grow.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-12-10T17:31:04.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433729/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433729/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-02","Small Businesses: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has conducted of the adequacy of the level of financial support offered to small businesses that have been in operation for two years or less; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","18526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433730","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-07","<br /><p>Higher Education Institutions have clear responsibilities under the Equality Act 2010 to support their students, including those with disabilities. <br></p><p>The Independent Office for Fair Access (OFFA) has agreed 183 Access Agreements for 2016/17 with plans for Universities to spend more than £745 million on measures to improve access and student success for students from disadvantaged backgrounds, up from £404m in 2009/10. HEIs choose their own access agreement measures and targets, in line with their own particular mission and challenges and these can include targets on disability where appropriate.</p><br /> <br />","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-07T14:43:36.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433730/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433730/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-02","Higher Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, whether access for disabled students will be included in measures to determine whether higher education institutions deliver effective outcomes for widening access and social mobility.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","18540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433731","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-13","<p>In 2013/14, 79% of Apprentices received formal training. In 2011/12 and 2012/13 the figures were 76% and 77% respectively. Information on formal training was not collected prior to 2011/12.</p><br /><p>In 2013/14, 80% of Apprentices received informal training, while in 2012/13, 85% of apprentices received informal training. . Information on informal training was not collected prior to 2012/13.</p><br /><p>Information on types of training can be found in the Apprenticeships Evaluation: Learners survey report online.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/387662/bis-14-1208-Apprenticeships-Evaluation-Learners-December-2014.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/387662/bis-14-1208-Apprenticeships-Evaluation-Learners-December-2014.pdf</a></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-13T17:38:29.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433731/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433731/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-02","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of apprentices received (a) formal and (b) informal training in each year since 2007.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","18542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433732","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-07","<p>The Student Loans Company (SLC) administers student support for each of the UK Government Administrations. Information on English loan borrowers is published annually by SLC in the Statistical First Release ‘<em>Student Loans in England: FY 2014-15</em>’.</p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment/england.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment/england.aspx</a></p><br /><p>The numbers of borrowers at the end of the 2014-15 financial year with post-2012 student loan arrangements who had been domiciled in (a) Salford and Eccles constituency, (b) the City of Salford and (c) Greater Manchester when they applied for financial support is set out in the following table:</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2" rowspan="2"><p><strong>Borrowers with post-2012 Loan Arrangements by Domicile (1)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Geographical Area</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Borrowers (2, 3)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Salford and Eccles</p></td><td><p>3,240</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>City of Salford</p></td><td><p>4,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greater Manchester</p></td><td><p>53,970</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Source: Student Loans Company</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Notes:</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>(1) Borrowers with loans outstanding as of 31/03/2015</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>(2) Excludes Further Education students</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>(3) Figures rounded to the nearest multiple of 10</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br />","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-12-07T14:45:53.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433732/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433732/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-02","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the number of student loan borrowers with post-2012 student loan arrangements in (a) Salford and Eccles constituency, (b) the City of Salford and (c) Greater Manchester.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","18575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433733","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-07","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-12-07T09:02:21.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433733/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433733/answer","18577 FINAL.pdf","18577 FINAL.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Earnings","UKSA Letter to Member - Earnings","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433733/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-02","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number of (a) full-time and (b) part-time employees earning less than £10,000 per annum.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","18577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433734","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-10","<p>A list of properties located in the Salford and Eccles constituency drawn from the central database of Government properties and land across the UK, e-PIMS™ is attached. A copy of this will be placed in the Library of the House. Government owned property can be found at:<a href="http://www.gov.uk/find-government-property" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/find-government-property</a>.</p><p>Information is only held centrally on the Central Civil Estate. Any information outside of this is held locally by departments.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-10T11:25:21.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433734/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433734/answer","GOVERNMENT PROPERTY IN SALFORD AND ECCLES 04122015.pdf","GOVERNMENT PROPERTY IN SALFORD AND ECCLES 04122015.pdf","PDF for Member- Government Property","PDF for Member- Government Property","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433734/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-02","Government Departments: Salford and Eccles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what Government property is located in Salford and Eccles constituency.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","18561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433735","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-09","<p>As has been the case under successive Administrations, civil servants, including special advisers, may routinely accompany their Ministers on official visits.</p><p>Information relating to Ministers' overseas visits are published on my Department’s website, as part of the Government’s wider transparency agenda.</p><p>All ministerial travel is undertaken in accordance with the Ministerial Code</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-12-09T16:25:30.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433735/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433735/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-02","Cabinet Office: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, on how many occasions a special adviser in his Department accompanied a Minister on an overseas trip since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","18495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433736","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-10","<p>As has been the case under successive Administrations, civil servants, including special advisers, may routinely accompany their Ministers on official visits. Information relating to Ministers' overseas visits are published on my Department’s website, as part of the Government’s wider transparency agenda.</p><p>All ministerial travel is undertaken in accordance with the Ministerial Code.</p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-10T16:07:26.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433736/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433736/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-02","Treasury: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on how many occasions a special adviser in his Department accompanied a Minister on an overseas trip since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","18511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433737","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-07","<p>5,244 tax credit claims that were investigated by Concentrix in 2014-15 resulted in the award being amended. Not all amendments changed the value of the award to the claimant. For example recording a change to the claimant’s income is an amendment to the award that does not always change the amount of the award.</p><p>There were 3,114 tax credit awards amended with a financial impact. The smallest amendment was £184, the largest amendment was £19,369 and the average reduction was £2,698.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-07T16:58:25.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433737/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433737/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-02","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many of the tax credit claims amended by Concentrix in 2014-15 resulted in a reduced tax credit award; and what the (a) smallest, (b) largest and (c) average value was of the reduction in such cases.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","18536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433738","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-09","<p>Reducing the income rise disregard to £2,500 brings forward some of the benefits of Universal Credit, so that tax credit entitlement reflects claimant’s recent earnings. It makes the system fairer so claimants on similar incomes will receive similar awards. The effect of reducing the income rise disregard on a family claiming tax credits will depend on the household’s income level before it increased.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-12-09T17:04:21.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433738/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433738/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-02","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 1.122 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what estimate his Department has made of the effect of reducing the income disregard on the household income of a tax credit claimant family with (a) two earners and two children, (b) one earner and two children, (c) two earners and one child and (d) one earner and one child whose income rose by £5,000 during the year.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","18553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433739","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-08","<p>The Government is committed to increasing compliance with minimum wage legislation and effective enforcement of it. Everyone who is entitled to the minimum wage should receive it. Employers who pay workers less than the minimum wage not only have to pay back arrears of wages at current minimum wage rates but also face financial penalties of up to £20,000 per underpaid worker.</p><br /><p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) enforces the national minimum wage (NMW) legislation on behalf of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS). It does so by investigating all complaints made about employers suspected of not paying the minimum wage, and carrying out targeted enforcement where it identifies a high risk of non-payment of NMW across the whole of the UK.</p><br /><p>I refer the honourable member to the answer provided at UIN 28587 for information on recovery of arrears and on the number of incidences of non-compliance on 26 November 2015.</p><br /><p>In 2014/15, HMRC issued financial penalties on 735 employers totalling £934,660 for non-compliance with NMW legislation.</p><br /><p>In 2014/15, HMRC completed 2,204 investigations as part of its duty to enforce minimum wage legislation.</p><br /><p>Any worker who believes that they are being paid below the minimum wage should contact Acas on 0300 123 1100. HMRC reviews every complaint that Acas refer to it but these may not always lead to an investigation. In 2014/15, HMRC received 2489 worker complaints via the helpline.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","18474 ; 18483","2015-12-08T16:33:29.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433739/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433739/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-02","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 26 November 2015 to Question 16850, how many (a) Notices of Underpayment and (b) financial penalties were issued to employers by HM Revenue and Customs for non-compliance with minimum wage legislation in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","18487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433740","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-08","<p>The Government is committed to increasing compliance with minimum wage legislation and effective enforcement of it. Everyone who is entitled to the minimum wage should receive it. Employers who pay workers less than the minimum wage not only have to pay back arrears of wages at current minimum wage rates but also face financial penalties of up to £20,000 per underpaid worker.</p><br /><p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) enforces the national minimum wage (NMW) legislation on behalf of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS). It does so by investigating all complaints made about employers suspected of not paying the minimum wage, and carrying out targeted enforcement where it identifies a high risk of non-payment of NMW across the whole of the UK.</p><br /><p>I refer the honourable member to the answer provided at UIN 28587 for information on recovery of arrears and on the number of incidences of non-compliance on 26 November 2015.</p><br /><p>In 2014/15, HMRC issued financial penalties on 735 employers totalling £934,660 for non-compliance with NMW legislation.</p><br /><p>In 2014/15, HMRC completed 2,204 investigations as part of its duty to enforce minimum wage legislation.</p><br /><p>Any worker who believes that they are being paid below the minimum wage should contact Acas on 0300 123 1100. HMRC reviews every complaint that Acas refer to it but these may not always lead to an investigation. In 2014/15, HMRC received 2489 worker complaints via the helpline.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","18483 ; 18487","2015-12-08T16:33:29.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433740/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433740/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-02","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many completed inspections were carried out by HM Revenue and Customs as part of its duty to enforce minimum wage legislation in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","18474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433741","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-08","<p>The Government is committed to increasing compliance with minimum wage legislation and effective enforcement of it. Everyone who is entitled to the minimum wage should receive it. Employers who pay workers less than the minimum wage not only have to pay back arrears of wages at current minimum wage rates but also face financial penalties of up to £20,000 per underpaid worker.</p><br /><p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) enforces the national minimum wage (NMW) legislation on behalf of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS). It does so by investigating all complaints made about employers suspected of not paying the minimum wage, and carrying out targeted enforcement where it identifies a high risk of non-payment of NMW across the whole of the UK.</p><br /><p>I refer the honourable member to the answer provided at UIN 28587 for information on recovery of arrears and on the number of incidences of non-compliance on 26 November 2015.</p><br /><p>In 2014/15, HMRC issued financial penalties on 735 employers totalling £934,660 for non-compliance with NMW legislation.</p><br /><p>In 2014/15, HMRC completed 2,204 investigations as part of its duty to enforce minimum wage legislation.</p><br /><p>Any worker who believes that they are being paid below the minimum wage should contact Acas on 0300 123 1100. HMRC reviews every complaint that Acas refer to it but these may not always lead to an investigation. In 2014/15, HMRC received 2489 worker complaints via the helpline.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","18474 ; 18487","2015-12-08T16:33:29.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433741/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433741/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-02","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many complaints from workers were received by HM Revenue and Customs on non-compliance with minimum wage legislation in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","18483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433742","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-09","<p>As part of the European reform agenda the Government is negotiating ensure competitiveness is embedded in the DNA of the EU, so that the UK financial sector can continue to thrive as the global centre of European finance. The Government is also negotiating to ensure that the UK remains able to effectively safeguard the stability and integrity of the UK’s financial system. This means ensuring that UK regulators have responsibility for financial stability and supervision in the UK.</p><br /><p>The City of London does not, however, get special treatment in the Government’s reform agenda. A special protection for the UK financial sector would not be in the interests of the single market in financial services, from which the UK benefits. Instead, we are demanding that the single market works in the interest of all 28 Member States.</p><br />","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-12-09T17:17:37.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433742/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433742/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-02","Financial Services: City of London","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to ensure that the status of the City of London as a world financial centre is explicitly protected during the renegotiations on the UK's membership of the EU.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","18443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433743","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-08","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that individuals are equipped and empowered to make informed decisions about how to use their pension savings through the Pension Wise service.</p><br /><p>The Financial Conduct Authority’s (FCA) standards for the service state that guidance should provide the consumer with information about long-term care needs, sustainability of income in retirement and life expectancy, to the extent that they are relevant. Pension Wise guidance therefore prompts consumers to think about their retirement objectives and wider financial circumstances when deciding on what to do with their pension pot. As part of this consumers are asked about whether they receive any benefits, other retirement income, outgoings in retirement, and plans to continue working. The guidance is designed to equip consumers to consider questions about their situation as a whole, and directs them to further sources of information as suitable. Where it is clear that consumers need specialist help, they are directed to the appropriate source of guidance and information.</p><br /><p>Pension Wise is constantly assessing and evaluating the service to ensure that user needs are met. As such, it is currently actively considering a number of developments, as part of our continuous service improvement, to make Pension Wise even more useful to consumers, including tailoring session content more closely to individual circumstances.</p><br /> <br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-08T14:54:13.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433743/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433743/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-02","Pensions: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of expanding Pension Wise to include consideration of housing wealth as a source of retirement income.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","18444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433744","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Government has not made an estimate of the National Minimum Wage (NMW) rates for these age groups for each year until 2020.</p><p /> <p>The Government asks the Low Pay Commission to make NMW rate recommendations each year based on maximising the wages of the low paid without damaging employment opportunities. The Low Pay Commission will recommend the October 2016 NMW rates and indicative rates for 2017 by the end of February 2016.</p><p><strong></strong></p><br />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","21821","2016-01-14T15:47:29.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433744/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433744/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-02","Minimum Wage: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the level of the National Minimum Wage for people aged (a) 16 to 17 years, (b) 18 to 20 years and (c) 21 to 24 years in each year until 2020.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","18568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433745","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-07","<p>The government will publish a National Infrastructure Delivery Plan next spring, setting out in detail how it will deliver key projects and programmes over the next 5 years. This will be underpinned by a refreshed National Infrastructure Pipeline.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-12-07T17:42:56.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433745/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433745/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-02","Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department plans to publish an update of the National Infrastructure Plan and infrastructure pipeline before the end of 2015.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","18541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433746","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-10","<p>The government is committed to moving the UK from a high tax, high welfare, low wage society to a lower tax, lower welfare, higher wage society. This remains the case, and Universal Credit (UC) is delivering this.</p><p>UC is fundamentally different from the current legacy benefit system and supports people into work and encourages them to earn more.</p><p>Therefore there is no meaningful way of comparing an unreformed Tax Credit system with UC. The Government has committed to transitional arrangements as we reform the benefits and Tax Credit system. Those transferred by DWP from tax credits to UC will receive Transitional Protection. In addition, estimates of entitlements under UC of the sort requested will vary depending on assumptions on the level of earnings.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","18557 ; 18586","2015-12-10T16:05:29.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433746/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433746/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-02","Welfare Tax Credits: Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what modelling his Department has done to estimate the potential effect on household income for tax credit claimant families who are migrated to universal credit before 2020; and if he will place that modelling in the Library.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","18559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433747","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-10","<p>The government is committed to moving the UK from a high tax, high welfare, low wage society to a lower tax, lower welfare, higher wage society. This remains the case, and Universal Credit (UC) is delivering this.</p><p>UC is fundamentally different from the current legacy benefit system and supports people into work and encourages them to earn more.</p><p>Therefore there is no meaningful way of comparing an unreformed Tax Credit system with UC. The Government has committed to transitional arrangements as we reform the benefits and Tax Credit system. Those transferred by DWP from tax credits to UC will receive Transitional Protection. In addition, estimates of entitlements under UC of the sort requested will vary depending on assumptions on the level of earnings.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","18557 ; 18559","2015-12-10T16:05:29.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433747/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433747/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-02","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 1.123 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what estimate he has made of the effect of uprating the individual threshold in the minimum income floor for self-employed people on the household income of a tax credit claimant family with two children and one self-employed earner under the age of 25 earning the national minimum wage.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","18586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433748","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-07","<p>The Spending Review set out that, if fully used, the additional council tax flexibility could raise nearly £2 billion a year by 2019-20. We will set out further details alongside the provisional local government finance settlement later this month, including an equality impact assesment in the New Year.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","18576","2015-12-07T16:53:09.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433748/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433748/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-02","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to paragraph 1.242 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, whether the Government carried out an equality impact assessment on the policy to allow local authorities to raise council tax by two per cent to fund adult social care.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","18574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433749","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-07","<p>The Spending Review set out that, if fully used, the additional council tax flexibility could raise nearly £2 billion a year by 2019-20. We will set out further details alongside the provisional local government finance settlement later this month, including an equality impact assesment in the New Year.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","18574","2015-12-07T16:53:09.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433749/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433749/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-02","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to paragraph 1.242 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what estimate he has made of the amount that the two per cent precept for adult social care would raise for each local authority if used fully.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","18576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433750","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-07","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p><br />","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-12-07T14:25:42.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433750/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433750/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-02","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of how many and what proportion of homeless people (a) are ex-service personnel, (b) have mental health problems and (c) identify as LGBT.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","18595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433751","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-08","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-12-08T13:07:13.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433751/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433751/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-02","Temporary Accommodation: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what management fee was paid to each local authority in Greater Manchester for housing tenants in receipt of housing benefit in temporary accommodation in the last financial year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","18560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433752","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-07","<p>My Department has run two targeted campaign bursts during 2015 to make sure eligible council and housing association tenants are aware of their opportunity to buy their home at a discount, through the Right to Buy scheme and to give them up-to-date information on changes to the discount rates and eligibility criteria.</p><p>We are currently in the middle of a burst of the campaign so figures for October and November are provisional and may not reflect all costs incurred. The monthly breakdown of invoiced expenditure for 2015 is:</p><p>January - £5,100<br>February - £68,600<br>March - £299,300 <br>April - £0 <br>May - £100 <br>June - £0<br>July - £200 <br>August - £600 <br>September - £64,700 <br>October - £155,000 <br>November - £171,200</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-07T14:28:14.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433752/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433752/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-02","Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much his Department has spent on advertising the Right to Buy scheme in each month of 2015.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","18460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433753","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-10","<p>The first 12 months of a refugee's resettlement costs are funded by Government using the Overseas Development Aid budget.</p><p>In November 2015 the Government announced around £129 million to assist with local authority costs over years 2-5 for those local authorities who are resettlling refugees under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme. This is unringfenced funding and it will be for local authorities to decide how to use the funding to support the refugees they resettle.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2015-12-10T16:46:41.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433753/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433753/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-02","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when the Government will inform local authorities of the increased funding that will be available for housing Syrian refugees.","false","Biography information for Paul Scully","Sutton and Cheam","Paul Scully","18463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433754","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-07","<p>The Jaywick Coastal Community Team are preparing their Economic Plan, to be completed by the end of January 2016. The Plan will outline the key economic issues facing Jaywick, setting out both the short term and longer term priorities for the Coastal Community Team.</p><p>The Chancellor confirmed at Autumn Statement last week that the Coastal Communities Fund will be extended from 2017-18 to 2020-21 with at least £90 million of new funding. Details of the next bidding round will be announced in the New Year. The focus of the Fund will remain on support for sustainable jobs and growth.</p><p>Tendring Council received £1.8 million in New Homes Bonus in 2015-16 and a total of £5.2 million since the scheme started in 2011-12. All new homes are constructed in accordance with Building Regulations, ensuring they meet minimum standards in respect of health, safety and sustainability.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-07T17:34:53.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433754/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433754/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433754/answer/previousversion/34130","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433754/answer/previousversion/34130",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-02","Regeneration: Essex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 15 October 2015 to Question 11444, when the regeneration strategy for Jaywick will be fully implemented; and if his Department will (a) provide additional resources to improve the (i) standard of housing and (ii) quality of life and (b) liberalise planning rules for house building in Jaywick and Brooklands.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","18488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433755","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-07","<p>We announced, as part of the outcome of the Spending Review in November, a £2.3 billion Starter Homes funding package to support the delivery of our manifesto commitment to build 200,000 Starter Homes by 2020. This is part of the £8 billion we are investing to deliver 400,000 new affordable housing starts. Further details about this funding will be announced shortly.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-07T14:26:44.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433755/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433755/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-02","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the amount of funding will be for the Starter Homes Local Authority Funding Programme in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","18525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433756","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-09","<p>Special Advisers have not undertaken any overseas trips with Ministers since May 2015.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-09T17:14:25.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433756/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433756/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-02","Department for Communities and Local Government: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, on how many occasions a special adviser in his Department accompanied a Minister on an overseas trip since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","18496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433757","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-14","<p>As has been the case under successive Administrations, civil servants, including special advisers, may routinely accompany their Ministers on official visits.</p><p>Information relating to Ministers' overseas visits are published on my Department’s website, as part of the Government’s wider transparency agenda.</p><p>All ministerial travel is undertaken in accordance with the Ministerial Code.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-14T15:50:04.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433757/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433757/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-02","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, on how many occasions a special adviser in his Department accompanied a Minister on an overseas trip since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","18497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433758","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-07","<p>The levy rate is set annually and is paid by bookmakers based in Great Britain, it does not currently apply to betting operators based offshore. The Government remains committed to replacing the current levy system to create a level playing field for British based and offshore gambling operators.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-07T15:44:11.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433758/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433758/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-02","Horse Racing: Betting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of changes in revenue from the Horserace Betting Levy arising from the activities of remote betting operators based offshore.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","18529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433759","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-07","<p>The Editors' Code of Practice sets out the rules and standards to which the press can be held to account. The Code is administered by the Editors' Code of Practice Committee and is evolving all the time to suit changing circumstances. Amendments to the Code can be suggested via the Committee's website:<a href="http://www.editorscode.org.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.editorscode.org.uk/</a>.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-07T17:13:05.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433759/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433759/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-02","Opinion Polls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will take steps to require newspapers and journals to publish on their websites what the questions asked, sample sizes and composition of people in terms of age, sex and ethnicity were for opinion polls cited in their publications.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","18490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433760","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-07","<p>To inform work to replace the current levy system, we have commissioned an independent economic analysis of the costs and funding of horseracing. This economic analysis work will also examine relevant comparable models, including the Australian system, however any reform of the Levy will need to comply with EU law.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-07T16:15:37.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433760/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433760/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-02","Horse Racing: Australia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment his Department has made of the (a) funding of horseracing and (b) effect of Race Fields legislation in Australia.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","18519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433761","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Working Class Movement Library is a private reference library and archive, run by a charitable trust. The most effective archives develop strong funding models to support sustainable, resilient and innovative services. The National Archives’ website provides information to help archive services develop fundraising strategies, identify appropriate funding sources and explore a range of fundraising techniques. More information can be found at:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/archives-sector/finding-funding.htm" target="_blank">http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/archives-sector/finding-funding.htm</a></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-17T11:54:20.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433761/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433761/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-02","Working Class Movement Library: Salford","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to paragraphs 1.207 to 1.212 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, whether financial support will be provided to the Working Class Movement Library in Salford.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","18562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433762","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-08","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) has committed to undertake a review on unsolicited marketing by consumer credit firms. This will take place early next year. The FCA intends to consult on any proposals in summer 2016.</p><br /><p>The FCA requires that when cold calling by phone, the identity of the person and the firm is made clear at the outset, as well as the purpose of the communication, so the consumer can decide whether to proceed.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-12-08T14:44:46.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433762/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433762/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-02","Nuisance Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Financial Conduct Authority plans to publish a consultation on nuisance calls.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","18538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433763","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-07","<p>Work is continuing on the detailed policy design of the replacement for the existing levy.</p><p>As part of the design work we commissioned an independent economic analysis of the costs and funding of racing. This will draw on information provided by betting and racing, and will be key to assessing what level of funding from betting to racing would be reasonable.</p><p>We will make a further announcement in due course</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-12-07T15:39:55.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433763/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433763/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-02","Horse Racing: Betting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to paragraph 2.144 of the Summer Budget 2015, what progress has been made on designing the Horserace Betting Right; and when he plans to publish his proposals on that matter.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","18530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433764","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-12-10","<p>The Government has been in contact with TalkTalk from the early stages of this incident, but this remains primarily a matter for the company itself and for law enforcement.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-12-10T16:34:59.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433764/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433764/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-02","Talktalk Group: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what information he has received from TalkTalk concerning the cause of its recent cyber-security breach and the measures it has put in place to prevent another such breach.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","18544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433765","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-10","<p>The Ministry of Defence's (MOD) policy for the capture, management and final disposal, including transfer to The National Archives, of the MOD's records is detailed in Joint Service Publication (JSP) 441-Defence Records Management Policy and Procedures. However it is important to note that not all documents are official records. The MOD only retains documents worthy of permanent preservation which are judged to have short or long term corporate value. For example a Training Centre may not retain attendance lists but the qualification attained would be included in the individual's service record.</p><p>A copy of JSP 441 has been placed in the Library of the House and can also be found on the Gov.uk website: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/jsp-441-defence-records-management-policy-and-procedures--2</p><p>JSP 441 advises that records relating to the development of the business unit's personnel or human resources through formally and informally delivered training activities, are to be retained for at least 15 years after which they are to be reviewed for on-going business reasons or potential historical value. These records may include records created by training centres relating to trainee attendance and courses held. If this review deems that these records are no longer required, then they are to be destroyed.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-12-10T17:18:06.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433765/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433765/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-02","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to version 4.3 of JSP 441 Defence Records Management Policy and Procedures, for what period training centres are required to maintain records in relation to (a) trainee attendance and (b) courses held; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","18551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433766","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-07","<br /><p>Due to the variation in course length (from one day through to 42 weeks), the number of courses completed is not recorded. Rather, delivery is measured on the number of weeks of training delivered. For financial year (FY) 2014-15, the number of weeks of training delivered at each centre is as follows (historical data is not held).</p><br /><p>Force Development Training Centre (FDTC) Grantown - 46 weeks</p><br /><p>Joint School for Adventorous Training (JSATI) Llanrwst - 41 weeks</p><br /><p>FDTC Fairbourne - 45 weeks</p><br /><p>FDTC Crickhowell - 46 weeks</p><br /><p>Information on the number of attendees is not held as costs are solely dependent on the maximum bed space capacity, regardless of the number of students attending.</p><br /><br /><p>Please see the information below giving the operating costs covering all locations for the last four financial years, for which information is available.</p><br /><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>FY 2011-12 £</p></td><td><p>FY 2012-13 £</p></td><td><p>FY 2013-14 £</p></td><td><p>FY 2014-15 £</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FDTC Grantown</p></td><td><p>295,624</p></td><td><p>220,819</p></td><td><p>213,781</p></td><td><p>231,290</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>JSATI Llanrwst</p></td><td><p>292,320</p></td><td><p>302,366</p></td><td><p>382,063</p></td><td><p>281,695</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FDTC Fairbourne</p></td><td><p>259,855</p></td><td><p>292,885</p></td><td><p>325,181</p></td><td><p>279,093</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>FDTC Crickhowell</p></td><td><p>688,808</p></td><td><p>654,010</p></td><td><p>646,027</p></td><td><p>643,985</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-12-07T16:50:33.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433766/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433766/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-02","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 30 November 2015 to Question 17694, how many training courses have been completed at (a) MOD Grantown-on-Spey, (b) MOD Llanrwst, (c) MOD Fairbourne and (d) MOD Crickhowell in each year from 2010 to 2015; how many students of each service attended each such course; what the cost of each such course was per trainee; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","18571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433767","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to her by the Minister for Defence Personnel and Veterans (Mark Lancaster) on 2 December to Question number 17679. Some costs for some previous years may be available and Ministry of Defence officials are reviewing them. I will write to the hon. Member and place a copy of my letter in the Library of the House.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-12-07T16:42:19.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433767/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433767/answer","20151202_17679_Military_Bases.docx","20151202_17679_Military_Bases.docx","17679 - QnA extract on Military Bases","17679 - QnA extract on Military Bases","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433767/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-02","Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 2 December 2015 to Question 17679, what the maintenance, improvement and development costs of (a) MOD Grantown-on-Spey, (b) MOD Llanrwst, (c) MOD Fairbourne and (d) MOD Crickhowell were in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","18570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433768","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-07","<p>The bed spaces at Force Development Training Centre (FDTC) Grantown-On-Spey, Joint School for Adventurous Training Instructors (JSATI) Llanrwst and FDTC Fairbourne have remained constant over the last five years. Since August 2015, FDTC Crickhowell has increased the bed spaces available from 80 to 260, at Cwrt-Y-Gollen Cadet Training Centre, which is adjacent to FDTC Crickhowell.</p><p>Bed space use is driven by the training requirement.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-12-07T16:52:25.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433768/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433768/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-02","Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 2 December 2015 to Question 17676, on military bases, whether those beds spaces have been consistently present and utilised in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","18572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433769","Ministry of Defence","true","2015-12-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to her by the Minister for Defence Personnel and Veterans (Mark Lancaster) on 2 December to Question number 17676.</p><p>The cost of bed and breakfast accommodation at Force Development Training Centre (FDTC) Fairbourne was £540.00 <ins class="ministerial">during financial year 2014-15</ins> and FDTC Grantown-on-Sprey was £1,920.00 <ins class="ministerial">as at December</ins>during financial year <ins class="ministerial">2015-16.</ins><del class="ministerial">2014-15</del></p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-12-07T16:49:55.117Z","2016-01-29T09:07:17.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433769/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433769/answer","20151202_17676_Military_Bases.docx","20151202_17676_Military_Bases.docx","17676 - QnA extact on Military Bases","17676 - QnA extact on Military Bases","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433769/answer","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433769/answer/previousversion/34106","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433769/answer/previousversion/34106","20151202_17676_Military_Bases.docx","17676 - QnA extact on Military Bases","11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-02","Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 2 December 2015 to Question 17676, how many nights bed and breakfast has been utilised at (a) MOD Crickhowell, (b) MOD Fairbourne, (c) MOD Grantown-on-Spey and (d) MOD Llanrwst in each of the last five years; and what the cost of that provision was in each case.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","18569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433770","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-10","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to her by the Minister for Defence Personnel and Veterans (Mark Lancaster) on 4 December 2015 to Question number 18405. Namely, the key documents will be placed in the Library of the House following the appropriate redactions and these will contain statistical data.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-12-10T17:19:22.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433770/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433770/answer","20151204_18405_Armed_Forces_Training[1].docx","20151204_18405_Armed_Forces_Training[1].docx","18405 - QnA extract on Armed Forces Training","18405 - QnA extract on Armed Forces Training","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433770/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-02","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answers of 2 December 2015 to Questions 17676, 17682, 17679, 17694 and 17681, what statistical data was used in the assessment process to close (a) MOD Fairbourne and (b) MOD Llanrwst; and if he will place in the Library a copy of the statistical data contained in his Department's Future Development and Adventure Training review.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","18552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433771","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-10","<p>The highest priority for UK based Force Development Training Centres (FDTC) is the delivery of Phase One and Phase Two formal training. The EAGLEs training scheme makes use of any irreducible spare capacity. Therefore, costs for EAGLEs training at UK based FDTCs cannot be separated out from overall training costs at those centres.</p><p>For Financial Year 2015-16:</p><p>EAGLEs training at FDTC Bavaria has a fixed cost per person estimated at £488.00.</p><p>The current projection for the planned 600 places for overseas EAGLEs training is £587.00 per person.</p><p>Overseas Eagles training is carried out in Austria, Germany, France, the Netherlands, Sweden and Norway.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-12-10T17:18:40.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433771/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433771/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-02","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 2 December 2015 to Question 17682, what the cost per trainee is of the Eagle training scheme at (a) Force Development Training Centre (FDTC) Bavaria, (b) FDTC Grantown-on-Spey, (c) FDTC Danesford/Weston on the Green/Halton and (e) overseas Eagles; and what the location is of the overseas Eagles training.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","18588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433772","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-07","<p>The two newly established staff posts in the Northern Ireland Universities Air Squadron were filled in October and November 2015, and the first students were accepted on 25 November. Of the 24 student places, 11 have so far been filled.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2015-12-07T16:51:45.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433772/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433772/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-02","Northern Ireland Universities Air Squadron","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what progress has been made on establishment of a Northern Ireland University Air Squadron.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","18580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433773","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-10","<p>UK airstrikes are undertaken as part of the Global Coalition's counter-Daesh campaign and are coordinated by the Coalition's Combined Air Operations Centre based at Al Udeid in Qatar. UK aircraft also abide by the provisions and procedures in the Memorandum of Understanding between the US and Russia which aims to prevent flight safety incidents over Syria and Iraq.</p><br />","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-12-10T17:04:27.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433773/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433773/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-02","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what planning he has undertaken to ensure that any UN airstrikes in Syria are (a) co-ordinated with all participating countries and (b) do not harm UN relations with the Russian Federation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","18467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433774","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 30 November 2015 to Question 17530 to the hon. Member for Coventry South (Jim Cunningham).</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-12-07T16:51:10.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433774/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433774/answer","20151130_17530_Armed_Forces_Deployments.docx","20151130_17530_Armed_Forces_Deployments.docx","17530 - QnA extract on Armed Forces Deployments","17530 - QnA extract on Armed Forces Deployments","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433774/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-02","Armed Forces: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 30 November 2015 to Question 17530, what information his Department holds on which foreign armed forces British military personnel were embedded within the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","18524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433775","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-07","<p>Force Development (FD) and Adventurous Training (AT) are governed separately. AT instructor to student ratios for each approved AT activity are laid out in Joint Service Policy (JSP) 419 (Joint Services Adventurous Training), which can be found at the following website:</p><br /><p>www.raf.mod.uk/rafhpa/rafcms/mediafiles/3033F0D5_5056_A318_A81B12353A721C24.pdf</p><br /><p>FD is a term predominantly utilised by the Royal Air Force and is made up of many delivery mechanisms, including AT, collective training and military exercises. The instructor to student ratio varies according to the activity risk assessment, which is carried out for each activity. Where AT is used as a delivery mechanism for FD, instructor to student ratios within JSP419 will be used.</p><br /><p>The policy for AT student to instructor ratios is regularly reviewed and updated.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier","18535","2015-12-07T16:48:26.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433775/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/433775/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-02","Armed Forces: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the ratio of students to instructors in Force Development and Adventure Training is; whether there is a different ratio of students to instructors for each of those activities; whether that ratio has changed in the last 10 years; whether he plans to review that ratio as a result of the Force Development and Adventure Training review; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","18491"
